						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">When you think about it, very little of a game program is about dealing with the hardware</div><br />In the case of the NES, it's not totally true. I found out at least half of my game's code is dealing directly or indirectly with the hardware.<br /><br />For example the player AI code is not dealing &quot;directly&quot; with hardware but you're still going to poll buttons press from the NES controller, so if you port it to another system a full rewrite will still be needed. The same for code that deals with printing or displaying anything on screen, etc... You won't be directly by writing to $200x, but the way you prepare your buffer and screen alignment is still closely related with hardware.</div>

